sublevels.theory:
Multithreading allows multiple tasks to run concurrently.

**Creating threads:**
```java
// Extend Thread
class MyThread extends Thread {
    public void run() { System.out.println("Running!"); }
}
new MyThread().start();

// Implement Runnable (preferred)
Thread t = new Thread(() -> System.out.println("Running!"));
t.start();
```

- `start()` — starts the thread
- `run()` — the code the thread executes
- Call `start()`, never `run()` directly (run() is not a new thread)
- `sleep(ms)` — pause the current thread: `Thread.sleep(1000);`
- `join()` — wait for a thread to finish

**`synchronized`:** ensures only one thread executes a block at a time:
```java
public synchronized void increment() { count++; }
// or block:
synchronized(this) { count++; }
```

**`volatile`:** ensures visibility of changes across threads (not atomicity).

**`java.util.concurrent` package:**
- `ExecutorService` — thread pool
- `Callable<T>` — thread task that returns a value
- `Future<T>` — handle to async computation

```java
ExecutorService pool = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(4);
Future<Integer> future = pool.submit(() -> 42);
int result = future.get(); // blocks until done
pool.shutdown();
```
